  "prompt": "What are the penalties for money laundering under federal law?",
  "response": "Under federal law, money laundering can result in significant criminal penalties, including:\n\n1. Potential prison sentences:\n- Up to 20 years in federal prison per offense\n- Potentially longer sentences if connected to other criminal activities\n\n2. Financial penalties:\n- Substantial fines, often up to $500,000 or twice the value of the laundered funds\n- Criminal forfeiture of assets involved in the money laundering\n\n3. Additional consequences:\n- Potential asset seizure\n- Mandatory restitution\n- Probation\n- Potential loss of professional licenses\n\nThe specific penalties depend on factors like the amount of money involved, the underlying criminal activity, and individual case circumstances. Prosecution typically occurs through statutes like the Bank Secrecy Act and Money Laundering Control Act.\n\nThese are general guidelines about federal money laundering penalties. For specific legal advice about a particular situation, consulting a qualified criminal defense attorney is recommended.",
